    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nWhen a line with a trailing word is automatically wrapped with `set ac fo+=t` the cursor is sometimes placed inside the first word in the wrapped line, specifically the leading character in the trailing word will end up at the start of the wrapped line.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n```\n$ nvim --clean\n:set fo+=t tw=9 ac\nia b c d<Esc>ie f g\n```\n\nObserve that `g` in the wrapped line is placed after `d` in:\n```\na b c e f\ndg\n```\nAnd that the line was automatically wrapped when inserting g at column 12.\n\n```\n$ nvim --clean\n:set fo+=t tw=10 ac\niab c d<Esc>ie f g h\n```\n\nObserve that `h` is placed after `d` in:\n```\nab c e f g\ndh\n```\nAnd that the line was automatically wrapped when inserting h at column 13.\n\nNote that when `tw=10` this does not happen with the specific example of `a b c d` unlike with `ab c d`, and that line is also wrapped when inserting `g` at column 12 with `tw=10`.\n\nAlso note that this does not happen with `set noac`.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe words should be placed in the same order as if they weren't auto-wrapped, or in other words, `g` and `h` should come before `d`.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.13.0-dev-4f7b6083e\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nVim behaves as expected, at least as far as I can tell\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nNixOS 26.05pre978060.3ec049d0d1b1 (Yarara)\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\ntmux 3.6a\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\ntmux-256color\n\n### Installation\n\ncustom nixpkgs overlay",
